---
layout: base
title: "Course: C to Rust Migration"
description: "Learn how to migrate a production C codebase to safe, idiomatic Rust one component at a time."
permalink: /c-to-rust-course/
og:
  image: /assets/images/rust/og-image.png
---

{% from "btn-primary.njk" import btnPrimary %}
{% from "btn-secondary.njk" import btnSecondary %}
{% from "color-hero.njk" import colorHero %}
{% from "strategy-list.njk" import strategyList %}
{% from "author-socials.njk" import authorSocials %}
{% from "contact-form-LP.njk" import contactFormLP %}
{% from "cta-banner.njk" import ctaBanner %}

{%
  set 'heroContent' = {
  "title": "Course: C to Rust Migration",
  "text": "Migrate your C codebase to Rust one piece at a time, without disrupting what's already running in production.",
  "eyebrow": "Rust Exercises",
  "image": "/assets/images/hero/c-to-rust-exercise.jpg",
  "alt": "A skybridge connecting two glass office towers",
  "loading": "eager"
  }
%}
{{ colorHero('purple', heroContent) }}

<main class="rust-exercises">
  <section class="container container--lg my-10">
    <h2 class="mb-2">You don't have to rewrite everything at once</h2>
    <p>
      Most Rust migration guides tell you to start fresh. That's not how it works in practice. Real
      codebases are large, deployed, and depended on. You need a strategy that lets C and Rust
      coexist while you migrate piece by piece.
    </p>
    <p>
      That's what this course teaches. You'll learn how to bridge C and Rust through FFI, expose
      clean Rust APIs to existing C consumers, and progressively replace C with safe, idiomatic Rust
      — without breaking anything along the way.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="rust-exercises-feature container container--xl my-10">
    <div class="rust-exercises-feature__content">
      <p class="text--accent">Free course</p>
      <h2>C to Rust Migration</h2>
      <p>
        Bridge C and Rust through FFI, expose safe APIs to existing C consumers, and migrate
        incrementally — without breaking what's already in production.
      </p>
      {{
        btnPrimary({
          "label": "Start the course",
          "url": "https://rust-exercises.com/"
        }, "white", "mt-2")
      }}
    </div>
    <div class="rust-exercises-feature__image">
      {% image "/assets/images/rust/c-to-rust-exercise-cta.jpg", "Mechanical gears representing a C to Rust migration", "(min-width: 62em) 45vw, 90vw", "lazy", "rust-exercises-feature__media", [760, 1440, 1920] %}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container container--lg my-10">
    <h2 class="mb-2">One concept at a time</h2>
    <p>
      The course follows the same exercise-driven approach as our other Mainmatter courses. Each
      chapter introduces a concept, explains the reasoning behind it, and puts you to work
      immediately.
    </p>
    <p>
      You'll start from the fundamentals — how languages communicate at the binary level — and work
      your way up to writing production-quality FFI APIs with proper documentation, ownership
      semantics, and error handling.
    </p>
    <p>No prior Rust FFI experience required. Basic familiarity with C and Rust is assumed.</p>
  </section>

  {%
    set topics = [{
    "title": "Foreign Function Interfaces",
    "text": "Understand how C and Rust communicate at the binary level. Learn how to expose Rust functions to C and call existing C functions from Rust."
    },{
    "title": "Types and Data Across the Boundary",
    "text": "Translate primitive values, strings, structs, and collections safely between C and Rust while preserving clear ownership semantics."
    },{
    "title": "Memory Management and Ownership",
    "text": "Design APIs that make allocation, borrowing, and deallocation responsibilities explicit across the FFI boundary."
    },{
    "title": "Error Handling and API Design",
    "text": "Convert Rust errors into predictable C-compatible results and build clean interfaces that are safe for existing consumers."
    },{
    "title": "Incremental Migration",
    "text": "Introduce Rust into a production C codebase one component at a time, keeping both languages working together throughout the migration."
    },{
    "title": "Production-Quality FFI",
    "text": "Add documentation, tests, build integration, and safety checks to create maintainable interfaces ready for real-world use."
    }]
  %}
  {{ strategyList('course-topic', '', topics) }}

  {% set mentor = 'JonasKruckenberg' | findBySlug %}
  <section class="workshop-authors container container--lg">
    <div class="workshop__content post__content--workshop">
      <h2 class="workshop-topics__heading">Your mentor</h2>
      <div class="author__wrapper">
        <div class="author">
          <div class="workshop-authors__image-wrapper author__image-wrapper">
            {% image "/assets/images/authors/JonasKruckenberg.jpg", mentor.data.name, '3.75rem', 'eager', 'author__lead-image', [120] %}
          </div>
          <div class="author__text-wrapper">
            <div class="author__name-wrapper">
              <h4 class="author__name">{{ mentor.data.name }}</h4>
              {{ authorSocials('JonasKruckenberg') }}
            </div>
            <p class="author__title large">{{ mentor.data.title }}</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="author__details mt-3 author__details--full-width">
          <p>{{ mentor.data.longBio }}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {{ contactFormLP('C to Rust exercises') }}

  {%
    set 'workshopCtaContent' = {
    "title": "Need hands-on training for your team?",
    "text": "We run workshops on C to Rust migration and other Rust topics, tailored to your team's codebase and experience level.",
    "linkUrl": "/services/workshops/",
    "linkText": "Book a workshop"
    }
  %}
  {{ ctaBanner('aqua', 'default', workshopCtaContent) }}

  <section class="rust-exercises-eurorust mt-10">
    <div class="rust-exercises-eurorust__image">
      {% image "/assets/images/rust/eurorust-2026.png", "EuroRust 2026 logo", "36rem", "lazy", "", [760, 1440] %}
    </div>
    <div class="rust-exercises-eurorust__content">
      <p class="text--accent">Community</p>
      <h2 class="h3">Meet other Rust enthusiasts at EuroRust</h2>
      <p>
        Mainmatter organizes EuroRust, a two-day conference covering Rust patterns, systems
        programming, CLI tooling, servers, WebAssembly, and embedded systems.
      </p>
      {{
        btnPrimary({
          "label": "Visit EuroRust",
          "url": "https://eurorust.eu/"
        }, "purple", "mt-2")
      }}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container container--lg opensource-list py-7 image-max-width-32" id="open-source">
    <div class="">
      <h1 class="opensource-list__title">You Might Like...</h1>
